<p>
This expression is used to mean "even if" or "even though" the conditon in the subordinate clause is true,
the action expressed in the main clause will take place. The main clause is not what would be
expected from the subordinate clause.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rain}}ga@KJ{{descend}}ttemo,@KJ{{wash^laundry}}shimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Even if it rains I'll do the laundry.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{day^weekday^day}}demo,@KJ{{work}}kimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Even if it is Sunday I will work.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
With a WH word @HI{{@Vte{{}}mo}} means "no matter WH".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{what}}wo@KJ{{eat}}betemo,oishii desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No matter what I eat it tastes good.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="ikura">@HI{{ikura}}</a> can be placed before the subordinate clause to indicate that a condition is about to be presented.
@HI{{ikura}} stresses the degree of conditionality.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ikura@KJ{{tall}}kutemo,@KJ{{buy}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      No matter how expensive it is I will buy it.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@Vte{{}}mo}} can be used to emphasise an approximate limit: "at most".

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{turf^reside}}ha@KJ{{long}}kutemo3@KJ{{time^interval}}de@KJ{{end}}warimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      That play will finish in 3 hours at most.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

